Bloom Filter
A Bloom Filter is a space-efficient, probabilistic data structure used to test whether an element is a member of a set.

The Naive Approach: Keep all billions of usernames in a SQL database or an in-memory HashSet. Checking it takes $O(1)$ time, 
but the memory cost is massive (gigabytes of RAM just storing strings).
The Bloom Filter Approach: You use a tiny bit array in memory. When a username is taken, you flip a few bits to 1.

If the Bloom filter says "No", it is 100% certain that the item has never been seen before. (Zero False Negatives).

If the Bloom filter says "Yes", it means the item has probably been seen before, but there is a slight chance it's a mistake. (Possible False Positives).

How it works - 
A Bloom filter consists of two primary components:
A bit array of size m, initially all set to 0.
A set of k different cryptographically independent hash functions (e.g., MurmurHash, FNV-1a). Each hash function must map an incoming element to one of the m slots in the bit array.

Step A: Adding an ElementWhen you add an item to the filter:Feed the item into each of the $k$ hash functions.Each hash function will output an integer index.
Set the bits at those specific indices in the bit array to 1.Example: Suppose we have a 10-bit array and 3 hash functions ($k=3$). We want to add the 
username "alice":
hash1(alice) = 2
hash2(alice) = 5
hash3(alice)= 8
Bits 2, 5, and 8 are flipped to 1.

Step B: Querying an ElementTo check if an item already exists in the set:
Pass the item through the same $k$ hash functions to get the target indices.Look at the bit array at those indices:
If any of those bits are still 0, the item definitely does not exist in the set (if it did, those bits would have been flipped to 1 during ingestion).
If all of those bits are 1, the filter returns true.

How False Positives Happen
Imagine you check for the username "bob". Its hashes point to indices 2, 5, and 9.
Index 2 and 5 were already set to 1 by "alice" earlier.
If another completely unrelated item happened to set index 9 to 1 in the past, all three bits for "bob" are now 1.
The filter will confidently tell you "bob" exists, even though "bob" was never added. This is a False Positive collision.

Usage:
1. Database Query Avoidance (LSM-Trees, Cassandra, BigTable)
When looking up a row key, databases have to read data from disk files (SSTables). Reading disk is slow. Systems like Apache Cassandra put a small Bloom filter in RAM for each file.
If the filter says the key isn't in that file, the database skips reading that file entirely.
This saves thousands of expensive disk I/O operations per second.

3. Content Recommendations / Cache Filtering (Medium, Squid)
Preventing users from seeing duplicate content. Medium can use a Bloom filter to track 
articles you've already read. When generating your homepage feed, it passes potential articles through your local filter to weed out read content without making heavy database joins.

Pitfals and Limitations - 
1. No Deletions Allowed: You cannot remove an item from a standard Bloom filter. If you try to delete "alice" by flipping bits 2, 5, and 8 back to 0, 
you might inadvertently erase bits that are also shared by other items in your system, introducing catastrophic false negatives.
  The Fix: If you absolutely need deletions, you must use a Counting Bloom Filter, which replaces the binary bits with numerical 
  counters that increment on insertion and decrement on removal.
2. The Filter Fills Up Over Time: The false positive rate ($p$) is a mathematical function of the number of items inserted ($n$), the array size ($m$), and the number of hash functions ($k$). 
If you keep stuffing elements into the filter without expanding it, the array will slowly become mostly 1s, causing the false positive rate to degrade toward $100\%$.
3. Non-Scalable Memory Size: A traditional Bloom filter is static. You must allocate the bit array size upfront based on your projected peak capacity. 
If your dataset grows $10\times$ beyond your estimate, you have to build a new, larger Bloom filter from scratch and re-hash your entire historical database into it.


Count Min Sketch - 
A Count-Min Sketch is a sub-linear, probabilistic data structure used to estimate the frequencies of elements in a massive data stream.

If a Bloom Filter answers a binary "Have I seen this?" question, a Count-Min Sketch answers a frequency question: 
"How many times have I seen this item?" It does this using a tiny, fixed amount of memory, making it an essential tool for big data processing and real-time streaming architectures.
You need to keep track of how many times every IP address or hashtag appears so you can find the "heavy hitters" (the top IP traffic or top trends).

The Naive Approach: Use a standard Hash Map (Map<String, Integer>). Every time a hashtag appears, increment its count.
  The Problem: If there are hundreds of millions of unique hashtags, your hash map will eventually run out of RAM, causing the application to crash.
The Count-Min Sketch Approach: You use a tiny, two-dimensional array of integers in memory. It tracks frequencies by routing elements through multiple hash functions.
  It never underestimates the frequency of an item. (Zero underestimation).
  It may overestimate the frequency of an item due to hash collisions.

how it works - 
A Count-Min Sketch consists of a two-dimensional grid of counters with a width $w$ and a depth $d$:The Grid Matrix: 
A table of dimensions d * w filled with integer counters, initially all set to 0.
Hash Functions: A set of d distinct pairwise independent hash functions. Each row in the matrix is mapped to exactly one unique hash function.

Incrementing an element - 
You pass $x$ through each of the $d$ hash functions.Hash function 1 tells you which column to look at in Row 1. 
You increment that specific counter by 1.Hash function 2 tells you which column to look at in Row 2. 
You increment that counter by 1.You repeat this down through all $d$ rows.

Query the element - 
Pass $x$ through the same $d$ hash functions to locate its associated counter in each row.
Read the values of all d counters.Take the absolute minimum value among all those counters. This minimum value is your estimated frequency.

Why do we take the Minimum?
Because multiple items map to the same grid locations, hash collisions will artificially inflate the counters. For instance, 
a high-frequency item might collide with "NVIDIA" in Row 1, inflating the count at Matrix[0][5].

However, because the hash functions are independent, it is highly unlikely that the same interfering item will collide with "NVIDIA" across all rows. 
Therefore, the row with the lowest value represents the path with the least collision noise, yielding the closest approximation to the true frequency.
use cases - 
1. Identifying Top-K Heavy Hitters (Trending Topics)
2. Network Traffic & DDoS Mitigation - To detect a Distributed Denial of Service (DDoS) attack, the router must track packet frequencies per IP address. A Count-Min Sketch allows
the router to instantly identify if an IP address is hitting it 50,000 times a second without running out of hardware memory.
3. Cache Management (TinyLFU in Caffeine Cache) - High-performance system caching engines use a Count-Min Sketch to track incoming item access frequencies. 
If the cache is full and needs to evict an item,
it queries the sketch to see which item is accessed less frequently across history, maximizing the cache hit ratio while keeping memory footprint under a few kilobytes.

Pitfalls and Limitations
1. Saturated Matrix Error Over Time: As the stream runs continuously, counters only go up. 
If a stream runs indefinitely, the matrix will eventually saturate, causing every query to drastically overestimate frequencies.
Fix - The Fix: Implement a Aging / Decay Mechanism. Periodically (e.g., every 5 minutes or every 100,000 items), divide all counters in the grid by 2. 
      This decays old historical counts, naturally prioritizing recent frequency trends.
2. Bad for Low-Frequency Queries: While a Count-Min Sketch is exceptional at measuring highly frequent items, it is notoriously inaccurate for rare or low-frequency items. 
The collision noise from heavy-hitter elements will easily bleed into the slots of rare elements, making them appear far more frequent than they actually are.
3. No Way to Retrieve the Keys: The sketch stores counts, not names. You cannot iterate over a Count-Min Sketch to print out a list of all hashtags inside it. It can only answer questions
about keys you explicitly provide to it. This is why it must be paired with an auxiliary structure (like a Min-Heap) if your objective is to list the top trends.

